      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis index validation — comparator link absent",
      "description": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RHI) values were computed for all five flow-speed operating points specified in the COU. Predicted RHI ranged from 0.61 to 0.94 across the design space, with worst-case conditions identified at 3 L/min / 3500 RPM. The assessment narrative references the FDA benchmark experimental dataset (CDRH pump hemolysis study, 2021) as the basis for comparison and notes qualitative agreement with published trends. However, no formal comparedAgainst link to that dataset or any other experimental reference is recorded in this result object. The inference that model predictions are credible therefore rests on a narrative description rather than a traceable comparator binding, undermining the evidentiary chain required under ASME V&V 40 Section 6.",
      "achievedMetric": "RHI_max = 0.94 (below acceptance threshold of 1.0)",
      "validationStatus": "assessed"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/steadystate-comparator-mismatch",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary flow-field validation — steady-state comparator mismatched to pulsatile COU",
      "description": "Velocity and wall-shear-stress distributions predicted by the CFD model were compared against particle image velocimetry (PIV) measurements from the FDA generic pump steady-state benchmark (constant flow, 2.5 L/min, 3500 RPM). Agreement was within 8% RMS for axial velocity profiles. MISMATCH NOTE: The declared COU specifies pulsatile inflow waveforms representative of cardiopulmonary bypass circuits (cardiac frequency 60–80 bpm, stroke volume 70 mL), whereas the comparator dataset was acquired under fully steady, non-pulsatile inflow conditions. The inference that steady-state validation adequacy transfers to pulsatile COU performance is an undercutting inference-method mismatch (D3): the experimental conditions do not share the temporal flow structure that drives cyclic shear exposure and cumulative hemolysis in CPB use. This mismatch is acknowledged here but was not treated as a disqualifying gap in the overall assessment.",
